tives to engineers to workers and union representatives, give his study particular credibility and offer surprising insights into the organizational power struggles that determine the form and performance of new technologies.Thomas urges managers not to put blind hopes into smarter machines but to find smarter ways to organize people. As U.S. companies battle for survival in an era of growing global competition, What Machines Can't Do is an invaluable treatise on the ways we organize work. While its call for change is likely to be controversial, it will also attract anyone who wishes to understand the full impact of new technology on jobs, organizations, and the future of the industrial enterprise.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAppropriate technologyzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aManufacturing industriesxTechnological innovationszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aManufacturing resource planningzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aOrganizational changezUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aOrganizational change. 0aTechnological innovationsxManagement. 4aGeneral. 4aSocial Science. 4aSociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aThomas, Robert J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052008701940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091507740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520915077423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520915077/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles